content:
Nice clash. Only issue is that you say "MSB first" but don't explain what "MSB" means. It seems like this could be confusing to new coders, so maybe just writing "(most significant bit first - e.g. '01000001' = 65 => 'A')" would make it clearer?

This was very fun in Shortest mode. Managed to do it in 91 characters in Ruby. :)

✅ Approved the contribution.

Comment: I accept this cause it looks like a simple problem with a quick solution

Goal section
* Please fix the typos:
   • vise => vice
   • the a string => a string
   • sinlge => single

* You may format "NO DATA" as a {{constant}} and remove the quotation marks.

Output section
* Please mention "or {{NO DATA}}".

Thanks.

I made my first Clash last year called "Let's burn a Disc", which involves converting ASCII streams to 8-bit binaries then into a "pit-and-land" stream analogous to how CD and most digital optical discs store data. This Clash stems from the reverse program I wrote to check my tests. I wrote this a year ago too but basically forgot to show it to everyone... I hope you guys will like it too!
PS: I would say one of the most fun part about making a conversion puzzle is writing the reverse program for generating and checking your tests as well as verifying the solution code!
Thank you! I would assume that the output "NO DATA" falls under "a string that may contain any printable ASCII character"?

Well at least I won't interpret it that way.

It can be simplified like:
<<Line 1:>> The original ASCII string, or {{NO DATA}}.
